# Network Fundamentals: Understanding the TCP/IP Protocol Suite

This document provides a comprehensive overview of the **TCP/IP Protocol Suite**, tailored for network engineering students and professionals preparing for Cisco certifications (such as CCNA).

---

## 1. Overview: What is TCP/IP?
The **TCP/IP model** (Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol) is the conceptual and practical framework that powers the modern Internet. It defines how data is formatted, addressed, transmitted, routed, and received across a network.

While the theoretical **OSI 7-Layer Model** is excellent for conceptual reference, the **TCP/IP Updated Model (5-Layer)** closely aligns with actual internet architectures and modern networking standards.

---

## 2. The 5-Layer TCP/IP Model & Encapsulation
Data moves down the stack during transmission (**Encapsulation**) and up the stack upon reception (**De-encapsulation**). Each layer adds its own control information (headers) and handles a specific Protocol Data Unit (PDU).

| Layer Number | Layer Name | PDU (Data Unit) | Addressing Used | Core Protocols / Standards |
| :---: | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **5** | **Application** | Data | - | HTTP, HTTPS, SSH, FTP, DNS, DHCP |
| **4** | **Transport** | **Segment** | **Port Numbers** | TCP, UDP |
| **3** | **Network / Internet** | **Packet** | **IP Addresses** (IPv4/v6) | IP, ICMP, ARP, OSPF |
| **2** | **Data Link** | **Frame** | **MAC Addresses** | Ethernet (802.3), Wi-Fi (802.11), VLANs |
| **1** | **Physical** | Bits | - | Cables (Cat6, Fiber), Hubs, Electrical Signals |

